english:
  title: In Response to Gang Jung, Using the Characters of 'Return Going' Based on Su Shi's Ten Rhymes
  author: Kang Hi-maeng
  language: eng
  text: |-
    When shall I return?
    I command my servant to ready the humble cart.
    Onward, onward, grieving for what has passed,
    toiling ceaselessly along the road ahead.

    Clouds and trees obscure the spring light,
    the fields and gardens grow wild and rough.
    Yet companionship holds genuine delight—
    at times I bring my wine gourd along.

    Each day the spring radiance arrives,
    and I alone rejoice in solitude.
    My heart surrenders to pleasure's call,
    my head lifts to gaze upon distant views.

    When weariness comes treading the world's path,
    only in age does the wattle gate bring peace.
    A farmer calls to ask of my affairs—
    with him I wander and linger awhile.

    In the western fields there is work to do,
    my young servants speak of early spring.
    I send them to seek out the hidden ravine,
    to lead water from the spring beyond the hills.

    Windlight graces even the ancient pines,
    the sun is veiled by clouds heavy with sky.
    All things flow through their forms and transformations—
    feeling the season, I ask of the fields.

    Sorrow upon sorrow weighs upon me—
    how shall I find this path through the world?
    Sometimes I surrender all to fate,
    and what concerns me ceases to trouble my heart.

    Pleasure's joy returns mostly to wine,
    happiness settles in the zither's strings.
    There is a thin path at the eastern slope—
    proudly I climb to look down upon it all.

    Yesterday's wrongs cannot be undone,
    my return seeks only peaceful rest.
    In respite, tranquility embraces me,
    and homecoming awakens me to native hills.

    I draw the wine cup, gazing at distant peaks,
    leaning on my staff, I gaze at the clear stream below.
    The world's path grieves me with its burdens,
    but I alone wander free in the spring wind.

    Stepping from my door, I must ride the cart,
    yet journeying far, I cannot remain.
    The ancient pine knows when to return,
    the spring in the garden begins to flow.

    Already I have shed the illusion of self and world—
    why then should I sever myself from fellowship?
    Riches and honor follow Heaven's will,
    they are not things that mortals can seek.

    Day by day I grow more distant from the capital,
    when I wish to return, what hope have I?
    Weariness comes—truly I must cease,
    and in old age, I rest from all striving.

    The pine and chrysanthemum compose their beauty,
    wind and cloud of themselves enter into poetry.
    My gentle face welcomes kinfolk,
    and joy becomes known through the heart's own measure.

    At the eastern slope I can sing and whistle,
    in the ravine I find the rushing waters.
    When the wind stills, I sometimes row my boat,
    when clouds return, I stand alone at my door.

    I leave greeting and farewell to the children,
    and entrust my happiness to wine and goblet.
    As I grow old, my spirit grows weary,
    and the old grace of life no longer dwells here.

    Now that I know the truth of this present day,
    why should I regret the failings of yesterday?
    I open the wine jar—gladly there is wine,
    I enter my room—what matter if I lack fine robes?

    Gazing into the ravine where waters flow far,
    stepping beyond my gate where pine paths wind thin.
    As I pause in my walking, feelings arise again—
    the tired bird flies off into the clouds.

    With each affair I encounter, feeling abounds,
    knowing Heaven's way, I desire no glory.
    My native place holds kin I can trust,
    my servants greet me with joyful hearts.

    In age at last I comprehend the zither and books,
    in traveling I learn the lightness of my staff.
    The world's paths of departure and return grow dim—
    no more shall I seek the affections of men.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: This poem responds to Gang Jung's request by matching the rhymes of Su Shi's famous 'Ten Rhymes' while using the characters from Tao Yuanming's 'Return Going' ('Guiqulai'). It is a complex poetic exercise in Korean literary tradition.
  - key: ''
    value: References to 'eastern slope' (dongpo/東坡) evoke Su Shi's own retreat and philosophical acceptance of his circumstances.
  - key: ''
    value: The recurring themes of return, natural cycles, and transcendence of material concern reflect both Daoist and Neo-Confucian philosophical ideals important to Korean literati of this period.
